Trump versusâ€¦

Estimating head-to-head matchups using polling averages

peter phalen

2/10/2020

There is quite a bit of polling data on head-to-head matchups between candidates: â€œIf you had to choose between candidate X or candidate Y, who would you vote for?â€

Weâ€™re going to use polling data compiled by 538 to look at how Bernie Sanders is doing head-to-head against Trump, and then compare that to Bidenâ€™s performance. Weâ€™ll adjust our polling average for â€œhouse effectsâ€, which are systematic tendencies for polling firms to favor a particular candidate.

library(tidyverse)
library(brms)

Preliminary data prep

We get the raw data directly from fivethirtyeight, and then process it.

data <- read_csv("https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/polls-page/president_polls.csv")

data <- 
  data %>% 
  subset(is.na(state))  # national polls only

data$candidate_name <- factor(data$candidate_name)

# encode dates as... dates
data <- data %>%
  transform(start_date = as.Date(data$start_date, format = "%m/%d/%y"),
         end_date = as.Date(data$end_date, format = "%m/%d/%y"))

# polls are usually conducted over multiple days
# get the point midway between the start and end dates of each poll
data$date <- data$start_date + floor((data$end_date-data$start_date)/2)

#convert date to a numeric variable (we'll use this later for modeling)
data$julian <- scale(julian(data$date))

Bernie Sanders versus Trump

Weâ€™ll start by looking at Sanders versus Trump, restricting the dataset to the relevant polls.

# get sanders head-to-heads
sanders_rows <- which(data$candidate_name == "Bernard Sanders")
sanders_rows <- lapply(sanders_rows, function(x){seq(x, x + 1)})
sanders_rows <- do.call("c", sanders_rows)
sanders_v_trump <- data[sanders_rows,] 

# get rid of minor candidates
pence_rows <- which(sanders_v_trump$candidate_name == "Mike Pence")
sanders_v_pence_rows <- c(pence_rows, pence_rows - 1) 
sanders_v_trump <- sanders_v_trump %>% slice(-sanders_v_pence_rows)

haley_rows <- which(sanders_v_trump$candidate_name == "Nimrata R. Haley")
sanders_v_haley_rows <- c(haley_rows, haley_rows - 1) 
sanders_v_trump <- sanders_v_trump %>% slice(-sanders_v_haley_rows)

# also get a data frame for just Bernie's vote share 
bern <- sanders_v_trump %>% subset(candidate_name == "Bernard Sanders")
# and then Trump's
trump.b <- sanders_v_trump %>% subset(candidate_name == "Donald Trump")

First weâ€™ll plot the data to get a rough idea for how Bernie is doing.

sanders_v_trump %>% 
  # relevel just for the color scheme
  transform(candidate = relevel(candidate_name, ref="Donald Trump")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = candidate) + 
  geom_point() + 
  labs(caption="Data from 538")+
  ggtitle("Sanders v. Trump", subtitle="head-to-head polls") +
  geom_smooth() +  
  ylab("percent support")

These polls are conducted by various polling companies. Different polling agencies tend to have biases, if only due to methodological differences. Itâ€™s worth checking for these so-called â€œhouse effectsâ€â€“we plot the data by agency here.

bern %>% 
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct, color = pollster) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("Support for Sanders", subtitle="by polling agency") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  scale_x_date(date_labels="%b") +
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")

House effects are clearly visible in these graphs. For example, Emerson College seems to show consistently better results for Bernie Sanders than Fox News does over the same period of time.

bern %>% 
  subset(pollster %in% c("Fox News/Beacon Research/Shaw & Co. Research", 
                         "Emerson College")) %>%
  ggplot() +
  aes(x = date, y = pct) + 
  geom_point() + 
  ggtitle("% support for Bernie Sanders (v. Trump)") +
  theme(legend.position = "none") +
  ylab("percent support") + 
  facet_wrap(~pollster, scales = "fixed")

House effects like these lead us to underestimate the degree of uncertainty in the data. Weâ€™ll want to account for them in our model.

Adjusting for house effects

Weâ€™ll use Stan to specify a simple model of the Bernie versus Trump matchup that takes house effects into account.

fit.bernie <- brm(pct ~ s(julian) + (1|pollster), data=bern, control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95), refresh=0)
fit.trump.b <- brm(pct ~ s(julian) + (1|pollster), data=trump.b, control = list(adapt_delta = 0.95), refresh=0)

Weâ€™ll use the model to plot voter preferences for Bernie over Trump.

bern.pred.frame <- bern %>% transform(pollster = NA)
bern.estimate <- predict(fit.bernie, newdata=bern.pred.frame, re_formula = NULL, probs = c(.1,.9))
bernie.out <- cbind(bern, bern.estimate)

trump.b.pred.frame <- trump.b %>% transform(pollster = NA)
trump.b.estimate <- predict(fit.trump.b, newdata=trump.b.pred.frame, re_formula = NULL, probs = c(.1,.9))
trump.b.out <- cbind(trump.b, trump.b.estimate)

dem.col <- "#00BFC4"
trump.col <- "#F8766D"

# plot trump and bernie models together
bern.figure <- 
  ggplot(bernie.out) + 
  aes(x = date, y = pct) + 
  ylab("percent support") + 
  ggtitle("Sanders vs. Trump, accounting for house effects", subtitle = "80% credible intervals") +
  #plot Bernie's share of the vote
  geom_point(color=dem.col, alpha=.3) + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=Q10, ymax=Q90), fill=dem.col, alpha=.2) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = Estimate), color = dem.col) +
  #now plot Trump's share
  geom_point(data=trump.b.out,  aes(x = date, y = pct), color=trump.col, alpha=.3) + 
  geom_ribbon(data=trump.b.out, aes(ymin=Q10, ymax=Q90), fill=trump.col, alpha=.2) +
  geom_line(data=trump.b.out, aes(y = Estimate), color = trump.col)
bern.figure

The uncertainty intervals are a lot wider than those that appear in our first figure, which is appropriate and reflects the fact that polling agencies show measurable biases that obscure the true voter intention.

Joe Biden versus Trump

Now weâ€™ll do the same thing for Biden.

# get biden head-to-heads
joe_rows <- which(data$candidate_name == "Joseph R. Biden Jr.")
joe_rows <- lapply(joe_rows, function(x){seq(x, x + 1)})
joe_rows <- do.call("c", joe_rows)
joe_v_trump <- data[joe_rows,] 

# get rid of minor candidates

joe_v_pence_rows <- c(pence_rows, pence_rows - 1) 
joe_v_trump <- joe_v_trump %>% slice(-joe_v_pence_rows)

haley_rows <- which(joe_v_trump$candidate_name == "Nimrata R. Haley")

joe_v_trump <- joe_v_trump %>% slice(-joe_v_haley_rows)

trump.j.pred.frame <- trump.j %>% transform(pollster = NA)
trump.j.estimate <- predict(fit.trump.j, newdata=trump.j.pred.frame, re_formula = NULL, probs = c(.1,.9))
trump.j.out <- cbind(trump.j, trump.j.estimate)

# plot trump and biden models together
joe.figure <- 
  ggplot(joe.out) + 
  aes(x = date, y = pct) + 
  ylab("percent support") + 
  ggtitle("Biden vs. Trump, accounting for house effects", subtitle = "80% credible intervals") +
  #plot biden's share of the vote
  geom_point(color=dem.col, alpha=.3) + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=Q10, ymax=Q90), fill=dem.col, alpha=.2) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = Estimate), color = dem.col) +
  #now plot Trump's share
  geom_point(data=trump.j.out,  aes(x = date, y = pct), color=trump.col, alpha=.3) + 
  geom_ribbon(data=trump.j.out, aes(ymin=Q10, ymax=Q90), fill=trump.col, alpha=.2) +
  geom_line(data=trump.j.out, aes(y = Estimate), color = trump.col)
joe.figure

A year ago, Biden was performing better than Bernie Sanders against Trump. Thatâ€™s no longer true.
